SENATE RESOLUTION NO. 180
BY SENATOR DUPLESSIS
A RESOLUTION
To express the sincere and heartfelt condolences of the Senate of the Legislature of
Louisiana upon the passing of Sharon Courtney and to honor her life, legacy, and
contributions to the political fabric of the city of New Orleans and state of Louisiana.
WHEREAS, it is with profound sorrow that the Senate of the Legislature of
Louisiana has learned of the passing of Sharon Courtney on May 21, 2026, after a brief and
courageous battle with colon cancer; and
WHEREAS, Sharon was born in 1965 in Aberdeen, Mississippi, and graduated from
the University of Mississippi in 1987 with a degree in journalism; and
WHEREAS, after graduating, Sharon moved to Washington, D.C., and began her
career of thirty-eight years in government relations as a legislative assistant on Capitol Hill,
first, in the office of Congressman Larkin Smith and then in the office of Congressman John
Murtha where she spent five and one-half years focusing on health care and education issues;
and
WHEREAS, in 1994, Sharon moved to New Orleans, Louisiana, which she called
home for the next thirty-two years, ultimately becoming one of the loves of her life; and
WHEREAS, Sharon brought her valuable experience from Capitol Hill to Tulane
University where she spent over thirty years leading community and government relations;
and
WHEREAS, Sharon was a key advisor to Tulane's president, Scott Cowen, and
played a vital role in reopening the university after Hurricane Katrina's floodwaters
devastated the city and scattered students to other campuses; and
WHEREAS, Sharon was a champion for the rebuilding of post-Katrina New Orleans,
and her efforts led to the securing of two hundred seventy-five million dollars in crucial
funding for all the city's public and private universities; and
WHEREAS, Sharon was named a YLC Role Model by the Young Leadership
Council in the spring of 2006; and
