WHEREAS, during her tenure at Tulane University, she successfully managed
community relations and secured the city's approval for a new on-campus football stadium,
which helped to enliven the school's football program; and
WHEREAS, she was instrumental in kickstarting the New Orleans BioDistrict;
creating a strategic plan for the twelve-hundred acre economic development district aimed
at growing the biosciences sector; and
WHEREAS, in February of 2025, Sharon struck out on her own, founding Neutral
Ground Strategies and continuing her higher education work by helping the University of
New Orleans shore up its funding, all while in the hospital during her final days; and
WHEREAS, Sharon's professional work was not the only way she helped make New
Orleans a better place to live, she also served in leadership roles for various boards,
including Market Umbrella, ReNEW Schools, and the Data Center; and
WHEREAS, Sharon was often referred to as one of the few honest brokers left in the
policy world, and gained a reputation as a steadfast advocate of the truth, constantly striving
to make the world a better place; and
WHEREAS, Sharon was known to be a person of high moral character, respect,
honesty, and integrity, even when what she had to say was not popular; and
WHEREAS, Sharon had a deep love of New Orleans and its cultural traditions;
attending Jazz Fest every year she lived in the city, becoming a member of the Krewe of
Muses and the Krewe of Dolly, and purchasing Saints season tickets in 2006; later being
rewarded with a string of playoff games and a Super Bowl trip to Miami, Florida; and
WHEREAS, above all else, Sharon was a relationship cultivator, a generous and loyal friend,
and a consummate host, and she was happiest with a crowded table of family and friends in
her home where she often hosted dinners large and small; and
WHEREAS, her generosity was not merely hospitality, but generosity of the spirit;
and
WHEREAS, Sharon is survived by her husband, Chris Allen; her parents, Jim and
Diane Morgan; her siblings, Mark Courtney and Courtney Gregory (Clay), her beloved
nephews, Eli, Fen, Jax, and Clay, and a plethora of friends and colleagues who will miss her
deeply and remember her always.
